<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2015/05/28/webinar-jstl-to-thymeleaf-transitioning-your-template">Webinar: JSTL to Thymeleaf: Transitioning Your Template</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon news-and-events"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/news">News and Events</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/c910c2f6520a5977a836d74e86e07cb4?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<span class="author">Pieter Humphrey</span>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2015-05-28 07:41:00.0">May 28, 2015</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="2142" href="/blog/2015/05/28/webinar-jstl-to-thymeleaf-transitioning-your-template#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>Speaker: Phil Dutson, ICON Heath and Fitness </p>
<p>Thymeleaf is a fantastic template engine that can help you create sites faster and get code shipped. There exists however a problem, using th e template engine requires a mind-shift in how to get "normal" tasks accomplished. This leaves many developers in the lurch and frustrated. In this talk I will cover the common pitfalls that developers can avoid and give examples on how to solve the common problems encountered when switching from the venerable JSTL to Thymeleaf.</p>
</div>
</section>
